00:02:03.780 --> 00:02:07.820
So I'd love for you to tell
everyone about the album

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:13.360
and just how you were drawn to
the material and a little bit

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:17.960
about how the concept of "On a
Turquoise Could" came together.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:20.800
CANDICE HOYES: Well, it was
really a labor of love for me,

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:22.260
I'd say.

00:02:22.260 --> 00:02:23.960
And this is my debut album.

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:28.010
So it's been such an
exciting journey for me.

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:31.750
As you mentioned, I have
a liberal arts background.

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:33.730
And certainly,
history is something

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:35.580
that's always inspired me.

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:38.700
And I'd say Duke
Ellington is, for me,

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:42.680
the most prolific and
most quintessential

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:44.590
American composer.

00:02:44.590 --> 00:02:47.340
And I do have a
classical training.

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:49.610
But one of the most
pivotal moments for me

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:52.720
was singing with Jazz
at Lincoln Center

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:55.780
a couple years ago on a very
special project that was

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:57.960
composed by Wynton Marsalis.

00:02:57.960 --> 00:03:01.040
And that's someone that I've
always really looked up to,

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:06.180
as someone who has never
been impeded by a genre.

00:03:06.180 --> 00:03:08.520
He's a foremost jazz
musician, for anyone

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:11.320
who's not familiar with
him, amazing trumpeter.

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:14.710
But he also draws from
many musical influences,

00:03:14.710 --> 00:03:16.440
as I always have.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:20.790
And so when I did that
gig, I just started really

00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:24.310
opening my mind, like what
could my first album be about?

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:26.600
What could be the
subject matter?

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:29.010
And so I did go back
to Duke Ellington.

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:33.990
And it's been a lifelong
source of musical inspiration.

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:36.280
He's such a innovator.

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:38.580
And I started
exploring these songs

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:41.500
and come to find
through research, which

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:45.860
is where the good liberal
arts background comes in,

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:49.890
no one's recorded them, many
of them, since Ellington.

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:54.940
So we are the first of our
generation to share these.

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:58.010
I say we because some of
these amazing musicians

00:03:58.010 --> 00:04:01.490
recorded the album with
me, arranged to play it on.

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:05.060
And we certainly are living it
out as we tour all of-- these

00:04:05.060 --> 00:04:07.150
are some of my
favorite musicians.

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:11.260
So it's just been
an amazing journey.

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:17.630
And every time I tour and
every time I go to a new place,

00:04:17.630 --> 00:04:18.850
it's Duke Ellington.

00:04:18.850 --> 00:04:22.450
But I'm bringing something
very undiscovered.

00:04:22.450 --> 00:04:24.410
So it's a discovery for me.

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:26.880
And then it becomes a
discovery for the audience.

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:29.150
So it was really an
exciting time for me.

00:04:32.884 --> 00:04:35.050
ANDREW RALLES: It's just
absolutely beautiful music.

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:38.075
And I can't wait for you
to play a couple of tunes

00:04:38.075 --> 00:04:38.700
from the album.

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:41.520
But just on the
topic of discovery,

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:45.320
there are some songs on it
that maybe a lot of people

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:47.140
never heard before.

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:50.420
I think they're lesser known
than some of Duke Ellington's

00:04:50.420 --> 00:04:51.920
other material.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:54.160
But in particular,
he wrote a few songs

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:57.940
for classically
trained sopranos.

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:01.520
And I'd love for you to talk
a little bit about the women

00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:07.370
in the original recordings
and your connection to them.

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:12.840
CANDICE HOYES: Well, that really
touches on more people who've

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:14.600
very much inspired me.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:16.580
There was one
particular vocalist

00:05:16.580 --> 00:05:19.210
who Duke Ellington
really discovered.

00:05:19.210 --> 00:05:21.070
And her name is Kay Davis.

00:05:21.070 --> 00:05:25.030
And she was a classically
trained vocalist,

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:27.060
much like myself.

00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:31.370
Went to Northwestern in the '40s
and did her musical training

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:34.460
in the time when
conservatory was segregated.

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:36.870
So she was one of the
stars of her class

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:39.280
and was chosen to
be very featured

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:45.170
in her senior performance
opposite a white tenor.

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:47.180
And that was controversial
on that campus.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:48.060
And this is Chicago.

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:50.400
It's not even the Deep South.

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:53.760
And by great fortune,
Duke Ellington

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:56.770
came to hear her perform
her senior recital

00:05:56.770 --> 00:05:58.610
and discovered her talent.

00:05:58.610 --> 00:06:03.490
And whereas she was encountering
those obstacles in the academy

00:06:03.490 --> 00:06:08.060
and in classical music,
Ellington just saw the talent

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:10.780
and saw that she had
something to say.

00:06:10.780 --> 00:06:12.910
And so he brought
her into the band.

00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:17.270
And as you know, Andrew,
with your musical background,

00:06:17.270 --> 00:06:20.430
a lot of jazz musicians start
so very early on the road,

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:22.220
especially in those days.

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:25.400
So she really was coming from
the conservatory environment

00:06:25.400 --> 00:06:29.760
and just hit the road, traveled
through the Jim Crow South

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:32.880
with the Duke Ellington
band, the only lady

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:36.060
in the band for a
great stretch of time.

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:38.800
And Ellington started to
compose for her voice.

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:41.640
And so he wrote "On
a Turquoise Cloud,"

00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:43.830
for which I've named the album.

00:06:43.830 --> 00:06:47.340
And it's a wordless vocalise.

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:52.540
A vocalise is a classical
term of art describing using

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:54.370
the voice like an instrument.

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:56.890
And so there are no words.

00:06:56.890 --> 00:06:59.690
And just the vocal
musical texture

00:06:59.690 --> 00:07:02.810
joins into the
texture of the band.

00:07:02.810 --> 00:07:10.240
And so for me, that kind
of assimilation musically,

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:12.990
it has a lot to do with
how I feel about the album

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:15.926
because I feel like
I'm going through that.

00:07:15.926 --> 00:07:17.550
So it was a perfect
name for the album.

00:07:17.550 --> 00:07:19.700
But it's also a
way of remembering

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:23.880
Kay Davis and a way of
acknowledging what Ellington

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:26.780
did for artists like me, who
don't really have a category.

00:07:28.792 --> 00:07:30.000
ANDREW RALLES: OK, thank you.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.680
And I think we have
some images of Kay

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:33.735
and a few of the other singers.

00:07:33.735 --> 00:07:35.860
CANDICE HOYES: Yes, that's
Kay Davis in the middle.

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:36.568
Oh, it's labeled.

00:07:36.568 --> 00:07:37.410
That's even better.

00:07:37.410 --> 00:07:41.160
Adelaide Hall, Adelaide
Hall in the '20s.

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:44.570
And we're going to play
it one of those tunes

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:48.230
that she made famous
called "Creole Love Call"

00:07:48.230 --> 00:07:49.690
when we start playing.

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:57.086
And many people say that she
is the first person to scat.

00:07:57.086 --> 00:08:01.500
But her scatting was in that
soprano range and growling.

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:04.720
And so those are
some jazz terms.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.610
But basically, it
means there was

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:10.270
a lot of freedom and
improvisation in her singing.

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:13.170
But she was also a great lady
of musical theater and stage

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:14.400
and cabaret.

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:17.495
And Alice Babs
hails from Norway.

00:08:17.495 --> 00:08:18.310
No, Sweden.

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:19.070
I'm sorry.

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:23.370
Sweden, but Ellington was such
a international musical figure

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:27.070
that he really pulled his
voices and inspirations much

00:08:27.070 --> 00:08:30.480
as we do in this world, in 2016.

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:32.429
It's a global experience.

00:08:32.429 --> 00:08:34.179
Tech is a global experience.

00:08:34.179 --> 00:08:36.590
In music too.

00:08:36.590 --> 00:08:38.159
And so he had so
many influences.

00:08:38.159 --> 00:08:41.558
So we actually deal with
that music on the album too.

00:08:44.239 --> 00:08:45.280
ANDREW RALLES: OK, great.

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:48.910
Well, why don't we hear a
couple of songs from the album?

00:08:48.910 --> 00:08:49.959
Are we ready to--

00:08:49.959 --> 00:08:51.000
CANDICE HOYES: I'm ready.

