00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:41.170
And this tune is very
special because it's actually

00:17:41.170 --> 00:17:44.160
Duke Ellington's first
international hit.

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:48.680
And it started in 1927,
when Ellington composed

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:51.920
this tune, inspired
by another song

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:54.810
from a musical called
"Indian Love Call."

00:17:54.810 --> 00:17:58.090
And he called it
"Creole Love Call."

00:17:58.090 --> 00:18:01.670
Jazz was actually born in New
Orleans, as many of you know.

00:18:01.670 --> 00:18:05.450
And so he was really
claiming that piece

00:18:05.450 --> 00:18:08.820
of music, that musical idea
that was really popular

00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:13.500
and appropriating it for jazz
and really putting his spin

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:16.130
on it and calling it
"Creole Love Call."

00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:21.390
And originally, Billy
Strayhorn wrote those lyrics.

00:18:21.390 --> 00:18:23.310
And he wrote them
about-- the lyrics

00:18:23.310 --> 00:18:27.830
are like, [SINGING] "My love,
my love, my love, my love,

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:30.710
I see you across
the swamp my love."

00:18:30.710 --> 00:18:31.950
Something like that.

00:18:31.950 --> 00:18:32.850
And I'm from Florida.

00:18:32.850 --> 00:18:35.420
But the swamp wasn't
really turning me on.

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:41.090
So [LAUGHS] I said, I'm going
to write some lyrics for this.

00:18:41.090 --> 00:18:46.280
And so they do come from a
little bit of life experience.

00:18:46.280 --> 00:18:58.008
So without any further ado,
this is "Creole Love Call."

