00:27:15.870 --> 00:27:18.870
and come out to more
shows and hear us.

00:27:18.870 --> 00:27:21.260
But we're so glad to be here.

00:27:21.260 --> 00:27:26.580
We thank you for welcoming us
to Google and Talks at Google.

00:27:26.580 --> 00:27:32.010
And this last tune
is very special to me

00:27:32.010 --> 00:27:36.980
because it really expresses
the whirlwind of emotion when

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:39.920
you release your first album
and all the amazing people

00:27:39.920 --> 00:27:44.210
that you meet along the way and
the wonderful musicians that

00:27:44.210 --> 00:27:48.550
become more like family than
colleagues or even friends.

00:27:48.550 --> 00:27:53.790
And Duke Ellington actually
had a very specific bond

00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:58.560
with one particular musician
throughout his entire-- well,

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:00.790
from the moment
they met, they were

00:28:00.790 --> 00:28:04.680
kind of musically
inseparable, Billy Strayhorn.

00:28:04.680 --> 00:28:09.450
And so this melody, it's one of
the most famous jazz melodies.

00:28:09.450 --> 00:28:11.890
People know it as
"Lotus Blossom."

00:28:11.890 --> 00:28:17.860
But upon the death,
they added lyrics.

00:28:17.860 --> 00:28:20.610
Well, Alice Babs
and her collaborator

00:28:20.610 --> 00:28:23.080
added lyrics to
this melody to make

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:25.590
it a tribute to Duke Ellington.

00:28:25.590 --> 00:28:29.480
And so it's a really
beautiful tune called

00:28:29.480 --> 00:28:33.694
"Thank You for Everything."

