00:32:19.900 --> 00:32:21.990
ANDREW RALLES:
Let's do some Q&amp;A.

00:32:21.990 --> 00:32:24.561
We have microphones lined
up in the aisles here.

00:32:24.561 --> 00:32:27.474
If you have your questions
ready, mics are open.

00:32:27.474 --> 00:32:29.890
CANDICE HOYES: Even if you
don't have your questions ready

00:32:29.890 --> 00:32:32.150
and you just want to
say hello, tell me

00:32:32.150 --> 00:32:35.360
how you liked the music.

00:32:35.360 --> 00:32:37.170
Hi.

00:32:37.170 --> 00:32:39.380
AUDIENCE: So I was curious
about a couple of things.

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:43.617
One was I've never
heard any jazz

00:32:43.617 --> 00:32:45.200
with the kind of
vocalization that you

00:32:45.200 --> 00:32:47.840
did in "On a Turquoise Cloud."

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:49.230
Is that a unique piece?

00:32:49.230 --> 00:32:53.970
Or are there other pieces
done with that kind of vocals,

00:32:53.970 --> 00:32:56.510
either by Ellington
or other composers?

00:32:56.510 --> 00:32:58.930
CANDICE HOYES: There
really are, actually.

00:32:58.930 --> 00:33:02.910
I did my research for this album
by going back to this source.

00:33:02.910 --> 00:33:05.520
So I went to the National
Archive and researched Duke

00:33:05.520 --> 00:33:07.570
Ellington and had
his manuscripts

00:33:07.570 --> 00:33:11.560
in my hand, the actual penciled
manuscripts, transcribed, some,

00:33:11.560 --> 00:33:13.680
by Billy Strayhorn.

00:33:13.680 --> 00:33:15.950
And I found about 30 songs.

00:33:15.950 --> 00:33:19.160
So it was really
quite eye-opening.

00:33:19.160 --> 00:33:20.670
But they definitely exist.

00:33:20.670 --> 00:33:27.450
And I tend to think that
many classical and jazz

00:33:27.450 --> 00:33:29.680
and musical theater
compositions of today

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:34.350
are so influenced by this
kind of improvisatory use

00:33:34.350 --> 00:33:35.750
of that high range.

00:33:35.750 --> 00:33:39.420
I mean, a lot of people,
even from Minnie Riperton,

00:33:39.420 --> 00:33:44.340
a soul singer that so many
people know, use that range.

00:33:44.340 --> 00:33:46.740
And so it is something
that's really, I think,

00:33:46.740 --> 00:33:47.950
continued in the music.

00:33:47.950 --> 00:33:50.596
But it is particular
to Ellington.

00:33:50.596 --> 00:33:53.930
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:33:53.930 --> 00:33:56.210
AUDIENCE: Thank you very
much for the performance.

00:33:56.210 --> 00:33:58.500
I had a question I hadn't
thought about until you

00:33:58.500 --> 00:33:59.470
started performing.

00:33:59.470 --> 00:34:02.860
You had at least two
songs with new lyrics

00:34:02.860 --> 00:34:07.730
or new interpretations beyond
just the usual interpretation.

00:34:07.730 --> 00:34:10.310
And I wondered when you were
researching and preparing

00:34:10.310 --> 00:34:13.969
the albums, did you have
any trepidations about that?

00:34:13.969 --> 00:34:17.670
Because it's not that jazz
is sacred in the sense

00:34:17.670 --> 00:34:19.957
that it never changes
because it's always changing.

00:34:19.957 --> 00:34:21.540
But when you're
dealing with something

00:34:21.540 --> 00:34:25.290
like Ellington's
music or Strayhorn,

00:34:25.290 --> 00:34:27.429
I'm sure there's a body
of people out there

00:34:27.429 --> 00:34:30.210
who probably don't
want any changes.

00:34:30.210 --> 00:34:32.235
It's like, this is
the classic jazz.

00:34:32.235 --> 00:34:34.110
CANDICE HOYES: Oh, you
met some of the people

00:34:34.110 --> 00:34:35.394
that I met along the way.

00:34:35.394 --> 00:34:36.310
AUDIENCE: No, I just--

00:34:36.310 --> 00:34:36.920
CANDICE HOYES: It's true.

00:34:36.920 --> 00:34:38.650
AUDIENCE: It's just that when
I was first got interested

00:34:38.650 --> 00:34:40.350
in jazz, it always was an issue.

00:34:40.350 --> 00:34:42.230
I got interested in jazz
when the avant garde

00:34:42.230 --> 00:34:43.530
was coming along.

00:34:43.530 --> 00:34:47.540
And it was a big
all-nighter type topic

00:34:47.540 --> 00:34:50.010
of whether you know Archie
Shepp or whoever it would be,

00:34:50.010 --> 00:34:53.929
Cecil Taylor, whether they
were on the right track

00:34:53.929 --> 00:34:57.420
or they were just almost
like the French avante garde,

00:34:57.420 --> 00:35:00.510
just tearing down the old movies
so that their movies could

00:35:00.510 --> 00:35:01.020
come in.

00:35:01.020 --> 00:35:02.930
The same concept in jazz.

00:35:02.930 --> 00:35:05.490
You had the traditional
jazz artists and then

00:35:05.490 --> 00:35:06.700
this new group coming in.

00:35:09.170 --> 00:35:10.920
I'm not trying to make
this controversial.

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:12.753
But I wondered if this
was an issue for you.

00:35:12.753 --> 00:35:16.260
CANDICE HOYES: Oh, you hit
on the heart of the matter.

00:35:16.260 --> 00:35:18.670
The question is, if
I had any trepidation

00:35:18.670 --> 00:35:22.070
about really putting my
stamp on Duke Ellington

00:35:22.070 --> 00:35:25.470
music and Strayhorn
music on my first album.

00:35:25.470 --> 00:35:30.010
And yes, it did
take some courage.

00:35:30.010 --> 00:35:37.592
And it's a journey
that I continue to-- it

00:35:37.592 --> 00:35:39.040
continues to challenge me.

00:35:39.040 --> 00:35:43.400
But it's also the very joy and
the very opportunity of jazz

00:35:43.400 --> 00:35:45.340
is that--

00:35:45.340 --> 00:35:47.150
Actually, when Vincent
and I were on tour,

00:35:47.150 --> 00:35:49.710
we ended up talking a
lot about that, and some

00:35:49.710 --> 00:35:52.040
of our other colleagues,
that there's really

00:35:52.040 --> 00:35:55.620
an onus for all musicians,
especially jazz musicians,

00:35:55.620 --> 00:35:59.670
I feel, I believe, to record
and put your stamp on it

00:35:59.670 --> 00:36:04.390
and to leave your
mark in this legacy.

00:36:04.390 --> 00:36:08.430
And then I feel like I doubled
down on that sense of purpose

00:36:08.430 --> 00:36:11.390
when I got to the Archive and
saw that these manuscripts--

00:36:11.390 --> 00:36:13.880
first of all, they didn't
exist as lead sheets.

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:18.170
So that means, for the layman,
that we as vocalists couldn't

00:36:18.170 --> 00:36:20.510
even really choose them.

00:36:20.510 --> 00:36:22.060
They weren't really an option.

00:36:22.060 --> 00:36:23.820
So they had to be transformed.

00:36:23.820 --> 00:36:26.530
And they had to be transformed
by somebody who loved the music

00:36:26.530 --> 00:36:27.321
and believed in it.

00:36:27.321 --> 00:36:29.760
And I said, that's me.

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:31.300
And so it was a
very humble process.

00:36:31.300 --> 00:36:32.840
It continues to be
a humble process

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:35.490
because I revere those artists.

00:36:35.490 --> 00:36:39.250
But it's very much
what I was meant to do.

00:36:39.250 --> 00:36:42.920
So I can't imagine
it any other way.

00:36:45.629 --> 00:36:47.420
ANDREW RALLES: Do we
have another question?

00:36:47.420 --> 00:36:48.570
CANDICE HOYES: Yes, hello.

00:36:48.570 --> 00:36:49.200
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:49.200 --> 00:36:51.150
Yes, other than the
National Archives,

00:36:51.150 --> 00:36:53.740
where does one look
for unpublished

00:36:53.740 --> 00:36:56.900
or unrecorded
Ellington repertoire?

00:36:56.900 --> 00:36:59.120
CANDICE HOYES: So
one of the privileges

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:01.650
of this album, because
it's such classic music

00:37:01.650 --> 00:37:04.840
and it's so innovative
and its life.

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:07.047
It's not new.

00:37:07.047 --> 00:37:08.880
But I was actually
thinking about this a lot

00:37:08.880 --> 00:37:10.921
when I was thinking about
coming to Google today,

00:37:10.921 --> 00:37:13.290
the difference
between my generation

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:15.740
is always looking at the new.

00:37:15.740 --> 00:37:18.670
And I was thinking,
this album, as you said,

00:37:18.670 --> 00:37:20.810
it's music that I recovered.

00:37:20.810 --> 00:37:23.241
But sometimes innovation
doesn't come out of newness.

00:37:23.241 --> 00:37:23.740
Right?

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:26.370
Sometimes it comes out
of repurposing something

00:37:26.370 --> 00:37:27.970
that exists already.

00:37:27.970 --> 00:37:30.385
And so with that
said, this music

00:37:30.385 --> 00:37:32.010
has brought me to
all different spaces,

00:37:32.010 --> 00:37:35.100
not just Google, but also this
huge international Ellington

00:37:35.100 --> 00:37:39.000
convention that I attended
earlier this season.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.550
And honestly, the
National Archive

00:37:41.550 --> 00:37:44.360
is just the tip of the iceberg
for finding rare Ellington

00:37:44.360 --> 00:37:45.860
material.

00:37:45.860 --> 00:37:49.760
Some of my greatest sources
were through the oral tradition.

00:37:49.760 --> 00:37:51.800
We had the privilege
of recording

00:37:51.800 --> 00:37:56.292
with a dear friend and
someone we revere very much,

00:37:56.292 --> 00:37:56.875
Joe Temperley.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:04.660
He's an amazing
artist and actually

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:09.270
recorded one of his signature
songs on this album with us,

00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:11.220
which was a great privilege.

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:13.890
And he imparted a
lot of information

00:38:13.890 --> 00:38:15.432
about Ellington
and rare Ellington.

00:38:15.432 --> 00:38:16.890
So just through
the oral tradition,

00:38:16.890 --> 00:38:19.760
you can get a lot
of information.

00:38:19.760 --> 00:38:23.650
People present me with
DVDs of Ellington's films.

00:38:23.650 --> 00:38:26.770
For me, for one of the songs, I
didn't find it in the Archive,

00:38:26.770 --> 00:38:28.350
for "Violet Blue."

00:38:28.350 --> 00:38:31.975
Actually, there is no real
vocal manuscript available.

00:38:31.975 --> 00:38:36.990
And so I had to extract
the sound using tech.

00:38:36.990 --> 00:38:39.800
I had to extract the sound
from a old movie clip.

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:43.170
So I think anywhere that you're
curious to find Ellington,

00:38:43.170 --> 00:38:46.220
you can find a lot of gems.

00:38:46.220 --> 00:38:47.220
ANDREW RALLES: One more.

00:38:47.220 --> 00:38:47.940
CANDICE HOYES: Oh, don't be shy.

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:48.546
Come on.

00:38:48.546 --> 00:38:51.535
AUDIENCE: Well, so in the
process of that research,

00:38:51.535 --> 00:38:56.750
do you imagine maybe
there's undiscovered

00:38:56.750 --> 00:38:59.770
Miles Davis or Charlie
Parker or whatever out there?

00:38:59.770 --> 00:39:02.476
Are you thinking of
doing anything like that?

00:39:02.476 --> 00:39:04.300
Or are you going to
stick with Ellington?

00:39:04.300 --> 00:39:06.810
CANDICE HOYES: Oh,
well, I would say I'm

00:39:06.810 --> 00:39:08.354
going to stick with all of it.

00:39:08.354 --> 00:39:10.020
Your question was
like, what would I see

00:39:10.020 --> 00:39:13.560
for a future project upcoming.

00:39:13.560 --> 00:39:20.310
I will always be culling through
the artists who influenced me,

00:39:20.310 --> 00:39:22.800
including, yes, Miles Davis.

00:39:22.800 --> 00:39:25.830
There are many
artists wh0 ranging

00:39:25.830 --> 00:39:28.980
from Stevie Wonder, Yo-Yo Ma.

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:31.900
I have a lot of
different influences.

00:39:31.900 --> 00:39:33.670
I don't know what my
next project will be,

00:39:33.670 --> 00:39:36.820
if it will be about rare works.

00:39:36.820 --> 00:39:40.130
But it's certainly something
I'm very interested in

00:39:40.130 --> 00:39:42.280
because I think that,
as young musicians,

00:39:42.280 --> 00:39:47.390
it's important to enjoy that
music and really gain from it

00:39:47.390 --> 00:39:51.280
all the inspiration
that is in it

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:55.700
and to share it with our
peers in this generation.

00:39:55.700 --> 00:39:58.790
And so it's a part of
my purpose, I feel like.

00:39:58.790 --> 00:40:00.960
It probably will be a part
of everything that I do.

00:40:00.960 --> 00:40:03.780
But as far as the
particulars, I think

00:40:03.780 --> 00:40:06.430
the next project will probably
have more of my writing on it.

00:40:09.460 --> 00:40:13.230
AUDIENCE: So I was also curious.

00:40:13.230 --> 00:40:14.920
I mean, do you
think other artists,

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:16.970
like, in the National
Archive or other places,

00:40:16.970 --> 00:40:21.510
that there are more of these
kinds of undiscovered tunes

00:40:21.510 --> 00:40:22.020
out there?

00:40:22.020 --> 00:40:23.811
CANDICE HOYES: Are more
undiscovered tunes?

00:40:23.811 --> 00:40:24.750
Absolutely.

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:27.940
And as I was mentioning
before, there

00:40:27.940 --> 00:40:29.550
are so many ways
to describe them.

00:40:29.550 --> 00:40:33.990
Some of them are just by hearing
live music and meeting players

00:40:33.990 --> 00:40:37.170
and getting clues as to,
oh, did you check out

00:40:37.170 --> 00:40:38.490
this recording of that?

00:40:38.490 --> 00:40:40.220
And that can lead
you to the music

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:42.360
that you've never heard of.

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:46.350
But yes, I mean, there
certainly is rare music

00:40:46.350 --> 00:40:48.190
being discovered all
the time because there

00:40:48.190 --> 00:40:49.981
are a lot of people
who are very-- not just

00:40:49.981 --> 00:40:52.436
me-- very passionate
about chasing it down.

